        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @neumi17- Cheers. I just knew Spurs would dominate but be heavily susceptible to the counter attack. Leverkusen pretty much set out how to play against them. Poch likes to dominate when he can but in doing so leaves inviting spaces, particularly in wide areas. It was unsurprising that 81% of Monaco's attacks where down the wings since the average percentage for attacks down the wings before today was 78.5%. Just let Spurs send their full-backs high and attack that space. It's naïve from Pochettino, he could see it was a definite ploy from the first 3 games but he didn't change it for the Wembley game against Leverkusen and it happened again today. I know some will say most counterattacking happens on the wings because they are the fastest players, and that is correct, but if it's a chronic issue, you should alter your game-plan. I think he'll learn from this experience if Spurs make it to the champions league next season. If he doesn't then the same thing will happen.
